FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices on planes (but no mobile phone calls)
Passengers can now use their electronic devices for reading, work, games, music and the image of films from the departure to the landing, but not with the mobile phone, according to the new guidelines, which were issued on Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States.
But the passengers should not expect that these changes will be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented, drawn by the respective airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
The airlines, the FAA must prove that aircraft meet the new guidelines and that they have updated the training manuals for flight crew, as well as the rules for the storage of the devices in accordance with the new rules.
The FAA said that they have already received by some airlines plans that would expand the use of portable electronic devices on planes.
Under these airlines were also Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of the plan we could approve the expanded use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA announced in a statement.
Currently, passengers must switch smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They can only restart them when the plane reached an altitude of three kilometers and the captain is the green light.
Enter the landing the passengers need to disable them again and cannot run again, before the plane landed.
Under the new guidelines could allow airlines, whose planes are secured against electronic malfunctions, their passengers to use the equipment in the launch and landing on the tarmac, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other pilots who were converted into greater heights for the use of Wi-Fi should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Professional Association of professional flight attendants, welcomed the changes.
"If the new regulation is implemented safely, and we are working closely with the airline together in this regard, both sides will benefit from it," Glading said.
